<font color="#FF0000">TO BARRY SPATZ</font><br>
<tt>Wed Nov  5 22:34:08 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Barry Spatz,<br><br>
My opinions have been well known on the subject of namecalling for a long time. I don't like it.<br><br>
I have several friends who protested the war. I have known them for years. One of the dearest of them died from leukemia a few years back. He taught at the small college here (Tusculum college). I attended his funeral service. I can safely say that each person on this channel would be well satisfied to receive the type of memorial service that this man received. He was well liked by everyone. War protesting was only a small fragment of his life. Vietnam is only a small fragment of my life.<br><br>
We played chess, and I still feel remorse when I think of the times late in his life that I beat him - knowing full well he was not at the top of his game.<br><br>
He and I talked about the war some, but never once did he act as if he had some type of compensation coming to him - as you do. He did what he thought was right. I did what I thought was right. I was deeply saddened by his death. To me he was not just a war protester or a coward. He was a man who touched the lives of all he knew. A true intellectual who befriended people from all walks. Bright, intelligent, but not a snob. One of the greatest men I shall ever know.<br><br>
Your posts differentiate between resistors, draft dodgers, and those who fled to other countries. I see no difference. They opposed the war. After I got my fill of the war, I came home and became an angry veteran who also opposed it. I had a wife at the time, so I went to work, considering myself fortunate to have a job. <br><br>
Many of my brother vets were not as fortunate. Some came home terribly wounded in body as well as spirit. We have rehashed time and again about the way we were ignored or avoided. I don't have any malice towards anyone, anymore. But, just because I understand and am able to be broadminded, *doesn't* necessitate that my brother vets should do likewise. Some are unable to see the side of the protestor. Some never will. <br><br>
If you had really made the effort to walk in the shoes of those who served in Vietnam, you would be less preoccupied with being right. That takes compassion. I see very little of that in your posts. You have always referred to my voice as being &quot;levelheaded&quot;, but when I disagree with you, then you state that I &quot;have changed&quot;.<br><br>
Let me tell you who has changed. It is guys like Cook, who admit that my opinions have made him rethink things. Guys like Bob Isbell and Ed and John Ratliff, who have differences with me, yet accept me for who I am. They know how I feel about the war. sounds pretty openminded to me. I never said I was right and they were wrong, either. We learn to resolve our differences, agree to disagree, and work together. These take time and most of all, trust. Trust is not extended to liars - except by fools.<br><br>
There is no justifying telling lies - especially when an attempt to gain credibility is made.<br><br>
If you have proof that one of the posters is not what he says he is - post it. 
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


